AUDIO: 'Hello and welcome to lecture number three of my post labor economics series. This episode is about measurements and KPI. And while that might sound a little bit boring, uh the entire philosophy behind this is that which gets measured'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gets managed. All right, so let\'s get right into it. The number one question whenever you\'re uh dealing with econometrics and optimizing largecale systems such as a national economy uh where you\'ve got network effects and'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those sorts of things is what are you trying to optimize for? Now, of course, any kind of KPI usually hides uh a lot more details. GDP is a big crayon kind of number. Unemployment is a big crayon kind of number. Um, however, at the same'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time, some of these can be useful KPIs. So, to steer a post- labor economy, our metrics must spotlight demand resilience, not just raw production. For GDP, that\'s kind of the the big the big knob that everyone is'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trying to optimize right now. It originated in the 1930s. um and uh became kind of the first kind of like aggregate okay wealth of nations what are we actually optimizing for um and one of the things is that you\'re you\'re'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually measuring uh transactions so it\'s a consumption-based economy so the theory is that the more consumption that you have the better the economy is doing and you just kind of throw it all into one bucket uh all consumption is'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically considered equal uh another thing is labor KPI so that\'s what I mentioned so unemployment uh wage metrics those sorts of things. Uh it\'s kind of assumed that those that those uh metrics like you know number of jobs'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you have and number of and amount of payroll that that\'s a pretty good barometer of the economy. And certainly even if it\'s not perfect, just tracking that number over time is better than nothing. Same thing with GDP. Uh on an'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'individual level, it\'s not necessarily uh that each KPI is complete. it\'s that uh tracking it over time indicates something that is underlying uh an underlying truth about the economy. Now,'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of course, with automation coming, uh labor and wages are going to start going down. So, they\'re going to become a less reliable, uh marker of what\'s going on out there. GDP is not going anywhere.'

[02:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But at the same time, uh we need a way to capture uh something that that says like, okay, even if wages go away forever, we need an entirely new set of KPIs other than payroll numbers, uh'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unemployment, and those sorts of things. Um so, uh what you\'re looking for, an ideal KPI is something that is both, uh descriptive and prescriptives. So'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'descriptive means that it is accurately able to diagnose a problem and prescriptive means that it can uh indicate what you\'re supposed to do with that information. So right now the Fed, one of the primary tools that they have'

[02:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is changing interest rates. You can lower interest rates, you can raise interest rates and that has uh plenty of downstream impacts on lending and borrowing. And of course uh lending and borrowing is used to do everything from'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finance construction to finance workers and those sorts of things. Um however what we\'re proposing and what I\'ve mentioned uh in other videos about post labor economics is the EAI. So that is the uh economic agency index and this uh'

[03:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tracks household buying power in ownership not just wages. It\'s actually broken down into three components. So with all that being said let\'s introduce the economic agency index. The EI uh'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gauges how much household spending power is rooted in ownership returns versus wages or transfers. Um, so it\'s there\'s three comp three primary components that goes into the economic agency index and'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all this data is publicly available. Uh, and we\'re actually working I\'m working with a couple of people to build a dashboard uh about this so that we can actually just show here\'s the data. Let\'s see what it looks like over time. So number one is property share'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dividends, rents, interest, and capital gains boost the score because ownership income scales with automation. So the idea is that the entire idea of post-labor economics is that we organize uh aggregate demand around uh property'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh so property based incomes. Now wages form another component. Earned pay still counts but its volatility under automation earns a lower positive weight beta. Uh so the idea is when you\'re'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measuring this, you don\'t want to punish wages because if people are still able to make ends meet through uh through uh you know wage labor, great. Like that is fine. And and certainly I and others'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
